Summary — Batch-43 Day 2: Docker (Multi‑Cloud + DevOps + AI) — Stepwise, Topics, Commands and Notes

1) Session goals and setup
- Objective: Hands-on Docker fundamentals—install Docker, pull/run images, container lifecycle, volumes, port mapping, interactive mode, exec, stats, running multiple containers, basic troubleshooting, and containerized apps (NGINX, Jenkins, Ubuntu).
- Environment: Any cloud VM (AWS/GCP/Azure) or local VM — Ubuntu used in demo.
- Pre-steps recommended: apt-get update, create VM with >=30GB if needed.

2) Installing Docker on Ubuntu (VM)
- Key commands:
  - sudo apt-get update
  - sudo apt-get install -y docker.io
  - sudo systemctl start docker
  - sudo systemctl enable docker
  - sudo usermod -aG docker $USER   (optional: run docker without sudo)
- Note: If cloud image has small root disk, may need to resize and reboot.
- Reference docs: Docker Engine install (https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/).

3) Pulling images vs docker run
- Concepts:
  - docker pull <image> downloads an image from a registry (Docker Hub by default).
  - docker run <image> downloads (if missing) and creates + starts a container.
- Demo images used: nginx, mongo, redis, node, ubuntu, alpine, jenkins.
- Key commands:
  - docker pull nginx
  - docker images              # list images
  - docker run nginx           # run image (no ports or detach)
- Architecture note: docker client -> docker daemon. Daemon checks local cache then registry.
- Reference docs: About images and containers (https://docs.docker.com/engine/docker-overview/).

4) Port mapping (host VM ↔ container)
- Concept: Expose container service to VM/public by mapping host_port:container_port.
- Key commands/examples:
  - docker run -p 8080:80 nginx          # map VM port 8080 -> container port 80
  - docker run -p 80:80 nginx            # host80->container80
- Troubleshooting: If service not visible, ensure correct external IP, firewall/Cloud security group rules (allow port), and correct HTTP vs HTTPS URL.
- Note: When mapping to public internet, enable cloud VM firewall rules (GCP firewall, AWS security groups).
- Reference docs: Expose ports (https://docs.docker.com/config/containers/container-networking/).

5) Detached mode, naming containers, logs
- Concepts:
  - Detached mode (-d) runs container in background
  - --name sets human-friendly container name
  - docker logs <container> shows container logs (access logs, error logs)
- Commands:
  - docker run -d --name mynginx -p 8080:80 nginx
  - docker ps                   # show running containers
  - docker ps -a                # show all containers
  - docker logs mynginx
- Notes: If container exits immediately, use docker ps -a to find stopped containers.

6) Stopping, removing, and force removal
- Commands:
  - docker stop <container>     # stop gracefully
  - docker start <container>    # start stopped container
  - docker restart <container>
  - docker rm <container>       # remove stopped container
  - docker rm -f <container>    # force remove running container
- Best practice: Stop before remove; or use -f if necessary.

7) Persistence: Volumes and bind mounts
- Concept: Containers are ephemeral; store persistent data using volumes or host bind mounts.
- Commands/examples:
  - mkdir -p /home/ubuntu/docker/nginx/html
  - echo "<html>…</html>" > /home/ubuntu/docker/nginx/html/index.html
  - docker run -d --name mynginx -p 8080:80 -v /home/ubuntu/docker/nginx/html:/usr/share/nginx/html:ro nginx
    (bind host folder to container web root; :ro optional read-only)
  - docker run -d --name mynginx -p 8080:80 -v mynginxvol:/usr/share/nginx/html nginx
    (use named volume)
- Notes: Use volumes for persistence and separation of data from container image.
- Reference docs: Volumes (https://docs.docker.com/storage/volumes/).

8) Interactive mode and exec
- Concepts:
  - -it (or -i -t) runs container interactively (attach a shell)
  - docker exec -it <container> /bin/bash (or /bin/sh) to enter running container
- Commands:
  - docker run -it ubuntu /bin/bash    # run Ubuntu and enter shell
  - exit                               # exit container (container may stop if foreground process ends)
  - docker exec -it <container> /bin/bash  # open shell in running container
- Note: To keep a container running when starting a shell, run in detached mode or ensure a long-running process.

9) Running commands directly without interactive login
- Concept: docker run can execute a command in container and exit with output.
- Examples:
  - docker run --rm alpine date        # run date in alpine, container removed (--rm)
  - docker run --rm ubuntu ls /        # list root of freshly started ubuntu
- Flags: --rm removes container after run to save resources.

10) Container lifecycle and management commands recap
- docker ps, docker ps -a
- docker stats            # live CPU/memory/network I/O metrics for containers
- docker images
- docker rm, docker rmi
- docker inspect <container/image>  # details and configuration
- Useful: docker ps -q | wc -l   (count containers), docker ps -aq | wc -l (all)

11) Running many containers (loop/automation, Compose, Kubernetes)
- Approaches to run multiple containers:
  - Shell loop (demo): for i in $(seq 1 30); do docker run -d alpine sleep 1000; done
  - Docker Compose for multi-container definitions (recommended for services)
  - Kubernetes for large-scale orchestration in production
- Example loop command:
  - for i in $(seq 1 30); do docker run -d --name demo_$i alpine sleep 1000; done
- Notes: Monitor resource usage (docker stats) when spinning many containers.
- Reference docs: Docker Compose (https://docs.docker.com/compose/), Kubernetes docs (https://kubernetes.io/docs/home/).

12) docker stats (resource monitoring)
- Command:
  - docker stats               # shows CPU %, MEM usage, NET I/O, BLOCK I/O per container
- Use case: Identify high resource consumers when many containers run.

13) Image cleanup and size considerations
- Avoid installing unnecessary packages inside images/containers in demos (keeps images small).
- Commands:
  - docker system prune -a    # remove unused objects (images, containers, networks)
  - docker image ls           # list images and sizes

14) Containerized Jenkins and unlocking Jenkins
- Demo: Run Jenkins container and access via mapped port.
- Commands (example):
  - docker run -d --name jenkins -p 8080:8080 -p 50000:50000 jenkins/jenkins:lts
  - To unlock Jenkins: docker exec -it jenkins cat /var/jenkins_home/secrets/initialAdminPassword
- Note: If running inside container, files/commands exist inside container; use docker exec to run commands there.
- Reference docs: Jenkins Docker image (https://hub.docker.com/r/jenkins/jenkins).

15) NGINX roles and logs
- NGINX functions: web server, reverse proxy, load balancer, caching, media streaming.
- Container logs include access and error logs. Use docker logs or exec into container to view /var/log/nginx.
- Example path inside container: /var/log/nginx/access.log

16) Common interview-style architecture wording
- Explain docker pull/run flow from architecture viewpoint: client -> daemon -> local cache -> registry -> download image -> create container -> start process.
- Use terms: Docker daemon, registry, local cache, container runtime, persistent volume.

17) Troubleshooting checklist (visibility issues)
- Check: container is running (docker ps)
- Check: correct port mapping (-p host:container)
- Check: VM external IP and cloud firewall/security group allows host port
- Check: using http://<external-ip>:<host-port> (avoid https unless configured)
- Use docker logs and docker exec for inside-container inspection

